00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:10.229
So when we came to wanting
to update the application,

00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:13.549
as always, the first place we
started was with sketching.

00:02:13.549 --> 00:02:15.090
And there were a
few things we wanted

00:02:15.090 --> 00:02:16.919
to do with the
application this year.

00:02:16.919 --> 00:02:18.960
First off, there was an
updated information model

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:21.744
we were trying to work
into the application.

00:02:21.744 --> 00:02:22.910
There were some big changes.

00:02:22.910 --> 00:02:24.840
We're going to be pushing
to get more imagery

00:02:24.840 --> 00:02:28.470
into the application to
really bring it to life.

00:02:28.470 --> 00:02:30.260
And that was finally
arriving this year,

00:02:30.260 --> 00:02:32.340
so there was a lot we
wanted to do with imagery.

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:35.590
And lastly, always
most exciting,

00:02:35.590 --> 00:02:39.560
we wanted to introduce some of
the elements of material design

00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:42.200
into the application.

00:02:42.200 --> 00:02:43.160
So we have a challenge.

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:44.600
And this application
was obviously

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:47.770
shipping to existing
versions of Android

00:02:47.770 --> 00:02:50.630
out there without new
APIs and new support

00:02:50.630 --> 00:02:53.610
for all this crazy stuff
like real time shadows.

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:56.550
So we had to do a
conservative approach

00:02:56.550 --> 00:02:59.400
of what we could use
on earlier devices

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:03.050
as well as on newer devices
which got the L preview.

00:03:03.050 --> 00:03:07.220
We wanted to really show off
some of the great new design

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:08.820
features.

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:10.610
So like many of
you, we'd seen lots

00:03:10.610 --> 00:03:13.130
of the exciting output of
the material design team.

00:03:13.130 --> 00:03:16.400
They'd shown lots of great
explorations and videos

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:18.070
showcasing their
new design system

00:03:18.070 --> 00:03:19.300
and what it could produce.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:24.560
And we naturally wanted to dive
in and reproduce some of this.

00:03:24.560 --> 00:03:28.530
So our first instinct was to
rush straight to visual design

00:03:28.530 --> 00:03:30.550
and put together
some mockups of how

00:03:30.550 --> 00:03:33.290
we could apply the material
design principles to the I/O

00:03:33.290 --> 00:03:35.510
application.

00:03:35.510 --> 00:03:39.220
But as you can see from these,
some early explorations we're

00:03:39.220 --> 00:03:42.920
sharing with you here, these
weren't quite satisfying.

00:03:42.920 --> 00:03:44.800
It wasn't quite hitting
the right notes.

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:46.940
And what's more, the work
that we were producing

00:03:46.940 --> 00:03:48.670
felt somewhat disjointed.

00:03:48.670 --> 00:03:50.370
And this is a real
trap you can fall in,

00:03:50.370 --> 00:03:53.940
the temptation to rush
straight to pixels.

00:03:53.940 --> 00:03:57.990
So what we actually did was
to take a step back and really

00:03:57.990 --> 00:04:02.600
work out our information
models and our flows

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:05.999
before going to do the
visual design stage.

00:04:05.999 --> 00:04:07.790
MIKE DENNY: Yeah, so
what we ended up doing

00:04:07.790 --> 00:04:14.720
is dropping down a step to what
we're calling white frames,

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:17.300
if you look in the
Google design spec.

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:19.750
You can download a lot of
Adobe Illustrator files

00:04:19.750 --> 00:04:26.860
that give a bunch of blank
templatey feeling screens that

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:32.130
are not quite-- a little
bit more than wireframes,

00:04:32.130 --> 00:04:35.990
but a little bit less than
a visual design mock up.

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:37.920
And so in that kind
of intermediary step,

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:41.100
it allowed us to really
explore the challenges

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:45.200
that the update to
the app proposed.

00:04:45.200 --> 00:04:48.120
And the most difficult
thing, I think,

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:55.360
for us was to figure out how
to most simply show and allow

00:04:55.360 --> 00:05:01.140
for filtration and selection,
the collections of all

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:03.700
the different sessions
and sandbox events,

00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:06.270
and all the different things
you could do at the conference.

00:05:06.270 --> 00:05:10.000
We also had to think about
two different groups of users.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.580
About 5,000 people at Moscone
West in the conference hall

00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:15.710
would be using the app.

00:05:15.710 --> 00:05:17.660
And they'll be making
use of the indoor map

00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:21.150
to find which room they need to
go to watch a certain session.

00:05:21.150 --> 00:05:22.920
But the vast
majority of our users

00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:26.670
are people at home or
at I/O Extended Events

00:05:26.670 --> 00:05:29.770
who weren't able to attend
in person in San Francisco.

00:05:29.770 --> 00:05:32.660
So we wanted to really make a
great app experience for them,

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:33.585
as well.

00:05:33.585 --> 00:05:37.990
The interesting change in 2014
from previous years at Google

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:40.630
I/O was that each
session, instead

00:05:40.630 --> 00:05:43.620
of being part of a track
around a specific product,

00:05:43.620 --> 00:05:45.740
like the Android
sessions, or the Glass

00:05:45.740 --> 00:05:50.780
sessions, or the Chrome
sessions, this year

00:05:50.780 --> 00:05:55.290
the conference was separated
around functional roles,

00:05:55.290 --> 00:05:57.150
or what we ended
up calling themes.

00:05:57.150 --> 00:06:01.920
And those were design,
develop, and distribute.

00:06:01.920 --> 00:06:04.840
So you had those three
broad categories,

00:06:04.840 --> 00:06:10.800
those themes that gave structure
to the sessions themselves.

00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:15.200
But we also, of course, had
product specific topic tags

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:19.330
and business vertical tags
like commerce, retail.

00:06:19.330 --> 00:06:24.560
We had music, media,
games, Android, of course,

00:06:24.560 --> 00:06:28.840
Chrome, Go, all these
different-- just tons of ways

00:06:28.840 --> 00:06:32.915
to dissect and
create cross-sections

00:06:32.915 --> 00:06:36.970
of this huge jumble of
sessions and other content.

00:06:36.970 --> 00:06:41.020
And it really took a lot
of time and collaboration

00:06:41.020 --> 00:06:43.920
and arguing back and forth,
should this be a list?

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:45.350
Should this be a grid?

00:06:45.350 --> 00:06:49.290
Can it be a list on phones
and a grid on tablets?

00:06:49.290 --> 00:06:51.740
How do we do the filtration?

00:06:51.740 --> 00:06:56.110
Do you jump in and pick a track,
say show me only Android stuff?

00:06:56.110 --> 00:06:59.810
Or can you be a little bit
more fine grained than that?

00:06:59.810 --> 00:07:02.380
Where's the line
of filtering down

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:05.150
to really present the
amount of information

00:07:05.150 --> 00:07:09.220
that the user is looking for?

00:07:09.220 --> 00:07:12.120
So it definitely helped
us to take a step back

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:14.490
into the wireframe,
the white frame stage,

00:07:14.490 --> 00:07:17.230
and look more structurally
at the interactions

00:07:17.230 --> 00:07:19.255
of the different screens
and how the users were

00:07:19.255 --> 00:07:21.296
going to be moving
throughout the app

00:07:21.296 --> 00:07:22.680
and through the
different stages.

00:07:22.680 --> 00:07:24.660
NICK BUTCHER: Just one quick
note on the white frames,

00:07:24.660 --> 00:07:26.210
we've put a little
link in the corner

00:07:26.210 --> 00:07:29.130
here to download these
Adobe Illustrator files.

00:07:29.130 --> 00:07:31.130
But there's also some
community members

00:07:31.130 --> 00:07:32.470
that really already
stepped up and produced

00:07:32.470 --> 00:07:33.511
Sketch versions of these.

00:07:33.511 --> 00:07:35.230
So if you're
getting into Sketch,

00:07:35.230 --> 00:07:38.070
which I have been
enjoying a lot lately,

00:07:38.070 --> 00:07:41.130
I can add a link in the show
notes to find that, as well.

00:07:44.070 --> 00:07:46.220
MIKE DENNY: Yeah, so to
help facilitate the fact

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:48.570
that three designers
working across three time

00:07:48.570 --> 00:07:51.810
zones on this
really complex app,

00:07:51.810 --> 00:07:55.040
we ended up just
using Google Slides

00:07:55.040 --> 00:07:59.420
and drawing out shapes
in really rough ways,

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:01.650
because it allowed us to
make comments directly

00:08:01.650 --> 00:08:04.420
on specific areas
and have a discussion

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:07.696
in an asynchronous way.

00:08:07.696 --> 00:08:09.570
ROMAN NURIK: I want to
add something on that.

00:08:09.570 --> 00:08:13.457
I think that's really,
really critical.

00:08:13.457 --> 00:08:15.290
Something I always talk
about in development

00:08:15.290 --> 00:08:21.000
is your iteration loop,
how fast you can iterate.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:23.200
And I feel like
there are great tools

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:24.935
for iterating in development.

00:08:24.935 --> 00:08:27.740
You make a change to
some code, you push it,

00:08:27.740 --> 00:08:29.382
and it shows up on your phone.

00:08:29.382 --> 00:08:30.590
On the web, it's even faster.

00:08:30.590 --> 00:08:33.330
You make a change, and
you refresh the page.

00:08:33.330 --> 00:08:36.159
Here, when you do
design work, design

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:39.219
is an inherently
collaborative thing.

00:08:39.219 --> 00:08:40.260
Design is a conversation.

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:42.929
It's a conversation between
various people working

00:08:42.929 --> 00:08:44.687
on a product.

00:08:44.687 --> 00:08:46.520
And so I feel like the
integration loop here

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:48.530
was critical.

00:08:48.530 --> 00:08:51.460
To be able to build out these
new features pretty quickly,

00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:55.220
we really needed to be
able to have three people,

00:08:55.220 --> 00:08:59.370
again, across three
different time zones working

00:08:59.370 --> 00:09:02.470
on one thing in a
single, shared space.

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:04.230
Mike would put
together a screen.

00:09:04.230 --> 00:09:06.440
I would make a quick comment.

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:09.500
I would select the item
in Google Slides, the box

00:09:09.500 --> 00:09:11.250
or whatever it was,
make a comment on it.

00:09:11.250 --> 00:09:13.250
Mike would make some tweaks.

00:09:13.250 --> 00:09:16.200
Later on, I'd just push
something down a few pixels

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:18.980
so that there was some alignment
across different slides.

00:09:18.980 --> 00:09:23.650
But the overall environment
for Google Drive,

00:09:23.650 --> 00:09:27.061
basically using Google Slides
to collaborate on wireframes,

00:09:27.061 --> 00:09:28.310
worked out really well for us.

00:09:28.310 --> 00:09:31.680
Obviously, it's super,
super low fidelity.

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:33.060
But just to get
the point across,

00:09:33.060 --> 00:09:36.730
the information on the screen,
the general macro level layout

00:09:36.730 --> 00:09:37.609
was super useful.

00:09:37.609 --> 00:09:39.150
NICK BUTCHER: And
I feel like forcing

00:09:39.150 --> 00:09:42.310
us to work in low
fidelity really helped us

00:09:42.310 --> 00:09:45.090
to focus the conversation
on the zoomed out,

00:09:45.090 --> 00:09:47.780
rather than getting bogged down
in the minutia of the pixels.

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:49.837
It helped us to think
about the larger problems,

00:09:49.837 --> 00:09:51.420
like how are we going
to do filtering?

00:09:51.420 --> 00:09:53.086
How are we going to
display collections?

00:09:53.086 --> 00:09:56.202
Rather than getting too
bogged down too early.

00:09:56.202 --> 00:09:57.410
MIKE DENNY: Yeah, definitely.

00:09:57.410 --> 00:09:59.160
It's super interesting
to go back and look

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:02.440
at that slides deck because
everything at the bottom

00:10:02.440 --> 00:10:05.080
is like slide purgatory,
all of our rejected ideas.

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:08.080
Old slides, we just dragged
them to the bottom of the stack

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:09.692
and forget about them forever.

00:10:09.692 --> 00:10:11.441
NICK BUTCHER: Oh, what
it could have been!

00:10:14.440 --> 00:10:17.860
So after we really had worked
a lot on the wireframes,

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:20.540
we wanted to step
up and introduce

00:10:20.540 --> 00:10:22.590
a lot of the material
design elements

00:10:22.590 --> 00:10:24.580
that we were hugely
excited about working

00:10:24.580 --> 00:10:27.650
into the application.

00:10:27.650 --> 00:10:31.410
So we're going to go through
now some of our interpretations

00:10:31.410 --> 00:10:33.560
of what we felt
was most critical

00:10:33.560 --> 00:10:36.540
and how we interpreted
them into the application.

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:38.420
This isn't going to
be like a thou shalt,

00:10:38.420 --> 00:10:41.640
this is the only way you
can apply material design

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:43.240
to your application.

00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:46.470
In fact, we were actually
kind of working on this

00:10:46.470 --> 00:10:50.710
while the material design
spec was somewhat in flux

00:10:50.710 --> 00:10:53.030
and changing a little
bit, as these things

00:10:53.030 --> 00:10:55.650
are wont to do before
they get launched.

00:10:55.650 --> 00:10:59.230
So if some things we did don't
quite work for your application

00:10:59.230 --> 00:11:02.090
or have evolved since
then, that's fine.

00:11:02.090 --> 00:11:06.300
This is part of the
evolving design process.

00:11:06.300 --> 00:11:09.730
But some of the key things that
we definitely wanted to use

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:13.150
was the key lines
and layout metrics

00:11:13.150 --> 00:11:15.490
which material
design introduced.

00:11:15.490 --> 00:11:18.155
The idea of using these
print style layouts-- Roman,

00:11:18.155 --> 00:11:20.030
do you want to talk
about the key lines some?

00:11:20.030 --> 00:11:20.750
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, yeah.

00:11:20.750 --> 00:11:22.780
Well, the first thing
is that the key lines

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:26.420
are kind of like a
hallmark or a signature

00:11:26.420 --> 00:11:28.740
characteristic of a
material design app.

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:32.655
When you see some of that text,
some of the body copy aligned

00:11:32.655 --> 00:11:36.760
to that 72-bit key line,
that second key line,

00:11:36.760 --> 00:11:41.910
it is very much a signature
aspects of material design.

00:11:41.910 --> 00:11:45.961
It evokes material design, the
personality of the framework.

00:11:45.961 --> 00:11:47.710
And another thing I
just wanted to mention

00:11:47.710 --> 00:11:51.620
is that when I first saw this,
I was like, this looks great.

00:11:51.620 --> 00:11:54.650
This makes a lot of sense,
too, gestalt principles.

00:11:54.650 --> 00:11:57.620
When things are aligned,
they kind of naturally group

00:11:57.620 --> 00:12:00.200
together so you can
understand that these

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:02.650
are part of a
single, whole thing.

00:12:02.650 --> 00:12:04.210
It also makes it
much easier to scan.

00:12:04.210 --> 00:12:06.120
Your eyes don't have
to bounce around

00:12:06.120 --> 00:12:08.654
between different starting
points [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:08.654 --> 00:12:10.320
But besides that, it
kind of reminds me,

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:12.356
one of the things
that I allude to when

00:12:12.356 --> 00:12:15.270
I talk about this with
folks is this kind

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:16.580
of reminds me of textbooks.

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:18.910
When you look at print
design, print and designing

00:12:18.910 --> 00:12:22.240
for magazines or textbooks
and things like that,

00:12:22.240 --> 00:12:24.135
you kind of have your
primary columns--

00:12:24.135 --> 00:12:26.010
and I'm probably using
all the wrong language

00:12:26.010 --> 00:12:28.090
here because I'm not
a print designer.

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:32.054
You have your primary
body copy columns.

00:12:32.054 --> 00:12:33.720
And then, you have
stuff on the outside.

00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:35.050
Imagine a textbook, right?

00:12:35.050 --> 00:12:37.410
You have your primary
prose in the middle.

00:12:37.410 --> 00:12:42.490
And then, you have little asides
or other accompanying items

00:12:42.490 --> 00:12:45.340
along the sides in the
gutters in those margins.

00:12:45.340 --> 00:12:48.290
And so I look at this
as these key lines

00:12:48.290 --> 00:12:51.870
help establish
that middle column.

00:12:51.870 --> 00:12:56.485
And then, you have things
on the outsides like the Add

00:12:56.485 --> 00:12:58.500
to Schedule floating
