00:15:20.660 --> 00:15:24.529
But we could have done
96 or 104 on tablets

00:15:24.529 --> 00:15:25.695
if we felt it was necessary.

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:30.810
So let's talk about
surfaces for a bit.

00:15:30.810 --> 00:15:34.660
And this is actually one of
the biggest components actually

00:15:34.660 --> 00:15:39.390
looking at material design as
composed of four basic things.

00:15:39.390 --> 00:15:42.520
Surfaces and shadows are one
of the biggest things to me.

00:15:42.520 --> 00:15:44.980
And actually, there's a
design byte either out now

00:15:44.980 --> 00:15:47.090
or coming out from
Rich Fulcher where

00:15:47.090 --> 00:15:50.370
he talks about specifically
surfaces and shadows

00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:53.915
and how those effect the
universe, if you will,

00:15:53.915 --> 00:15:58.700
of apps following
this framework.

00:15:58.700 --> 00:16:00.470
And for surfaces,
he kind of alludes

00:16:00.470 --> 00:16:03.680
to surfaces as pieces of paper.

00:16:03.680 --> 00:16:08.820
And when a surface is
floating over another surface

00:16:08.820 --> 00:16:13.370
in the z space, it casts a
shadow on the surface below it

00:16:13.370 --> 00:16:14.830
or the piece of paper below it.

00:16:14.830 --> 00:16:17.460
And so we thought
a lot about this

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:21.682
because this is one of the key
components of material design.

00:16:21.682 --> 00:16:22.890
We thought a lot about this.

00:16:22.890 --> 00:16:25.181
And so that influenced
some of our decisions.

00:16:25.181 --> 00:16:27.555
NICK BUTCHER: So one technique
which we've not shown here

00:16:27.555 --> 00:16:32.660
in our mocks is ways to,
in your design stage,

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:40.640
show which level on the z access
a particular surface lives.

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:44.150
So we didn't use it at the
time of designing the I/O app.

00:16:44.150 --> 00:16:46.300
I've been using it in
my design since then.

00:16:46.300 --> 00:16:48.435
It's actually a call out,
so when you're specing up

00:16:48.435 --> 00:16:53.060
a screen, as well as when you're
calling out the color or size

00:16:53.060 --> 00:16:55.500
or shape, whatever,
it's to say that this

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:58.390
lives in a particular plane.

00:16:58.390 --> 00:17:00.020
So the way we've
been doing that is it

00:17:00.020 --> 00:17:02.478
helps to think about it in--
if you might have, say, three,

00:17:02.478 --> 00:17:04.895
four, maybe five
different z levels,

00:17:04.895 --> 00:17:09.630
you can call it z0, z1,
z2, z3, and call those

00:17:09.630 --> 00:17:13.839
out so that you can then use
those levels consistently

00:17:13.839 --> 00:17:15.009
throughout your application.

00:17:15.009 --> 00:17:16.800
So you might say that,
in your application,

00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:19.380
in the primary
content, there's a z0.

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:22.912
Whereas in this example
here, the bottom bar,

00:17:22.912 --> 00:17:25.450
the bottom section
lives at z level one

00:17:25.450 --> 00:17:26.890
and the floating
action button is

00:17:26.890 --> 00:17:29.300
on top of that at z level two.

00:17:29.300 --> 00:17:30.800
And then, what
you can then do is

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:32.700
when you hand that
over to developers,

00:17:32.700 --> 00:17:36.910
is decide what levels,
what dimensions and DIPs

00:17:36.910 --> 00:17:40.540
those levels of z work at.

00:17:40.540 --> 00:17:43.030
And then, transfer those
into actual dimensions.

00:17:43.030 --> 00:17:45.260
It's kind of like thinking
about an air traffic

00:17:45.260 --> 00:17:48.870
controller, where you're
thinking each of your UI

00:17:48.870 --> 00:17:52.864
surfaces is actually a different
plane, a different level.

00:17:52.864 --> 00:17:55.530
So you're trying to work out how
they stack on top of each other

00:17:55.530 --> 00:17:57.863
without colliding so they can
move underneath each other

00:17:57.863 --> 00:18:00.650
and give you that natural motion
you're trying to design for.

